<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-1099-errors-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;1099 errors,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A 1099 is the form you give certain vendors &mdash; mostly contractors and certain service providers &mdash; reporting what you paid them over the year. In QuickBooks that report is built from your vendor records, the W-9 data those vendors gave you, and the way payments are mapped to expense accounts. When people say their &ldquo;1099s are wrong,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: a vendor who should appear on a 1099 is <em>missing</em>; the dollar <em>amounts</em> don&rsquo;t match what they actually paid; or the forms simply <em>won&rsquo;t generate</em> for a vendor or a year.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes &mdash; vendors not marked as 1099-eligible, payments mapped to accounts left out of the box mapping, the $600 threshold, or credit-card payments that don&rsquo;t belong on a 1099-NEC at all &mdash; and the fix steps below address them in order. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> do is file the forms with the IRS or tell you which box a payment legally belongs in: the e-file goes through Intuit&rsquo;s 1099 e-file service or your CPA, and tax-rule questions are your CPA&rsquo;s. We get the QuickBooks data and mapping right so whoever files is filing the right numbers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

